e -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.post p</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>General sibling selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the most powerful selector. Most of the time when you have no solution to select a tag there always remains a possibility that we can select that with the general sibling selector. The general sibling selector selects <strong>all sibling elements of that element</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html>\r\n&lt;html lang=\"en\">\r\n\r\n&lt;head>\r\n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\r\n    &lt;meta http-equiv=\"X-UA-Compatible\" content=\"IE=edge\">\r\n    &lt;meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\r\n    &lt;title>Document&lt;/title>\r\n    &lt;style>\r\n        .post>.readmore~button {\r\n            background: red;\n            padding:10px;\n            border:none;\n            outline:none\r\n        }\r\n    &lt;/style>\r\n&lt;/head>\r\n\r\n&lt;body>\r\n    &lt;div class=\"main\">\r\n        &lt;div class=\"post\">\r\n            &lt;button class=\"readmore\">read more&lt;/button>\r\n            &lt;button>read more1&lt;/button>\r\n            &lt;button>read more2&lt;/button>\r\n            &lt;button>read more3&lt;/button>\r\n        &lt;/div>\r\n    &lt;/div>\r\n\r\n&lt;/body>\r\n\r\n&lt;/html></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n\n    <style>\n        .postart>.readmore ~ button {\n            background: red;\n            padding:10px;\n            border:none;\n            outline:none\n        }\n    </style>\n\n    <div class=\"main\">\n        <div class=\"postart\">\n            <button class=\"readmore\">read more</button>\n            <button>read more1</button>\n            <button>read more2</button>\n            <button>read more3</button>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Attribute selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTML element can also be selected based on its attribute whether it\'s a default or custom attribute.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>syntax of attribute selector</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;attribute=\"attribute-value\"]{\n\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>example </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;class*=\"col\"]{\npadding:-15px\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>some of the advanced methods of attribute selectors</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class*=\"col\"]<br>attribute value has a \"col\" word somewhere example : <code><code>&lt;div class=\"<strong>col</strong>-md-4\">&lt;/div></code></code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class^=\"col-12\"]<br>attribute value has a \"<strong>col</strong>\" word in starting example : <code>&lt;div class=\"<strong>col-12</strong> col-md-4\">&lt;/div></code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class$=\"col\"]<br>class tribute has the value \"<strong>col-12</strong>\" word at the end <br>example : <code>&lt;div class=\"<code>col-md-4</code> <strong>col-12</strong>\">&lt;/div></code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class=\"col\"] <br>the attribute value is exactly \"col\"<br>example <code>&lt;div class=\"<code>col</code>\">&lt;/div></code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Adjacent sibling selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An adjacent sibling selector is used to select just the next sibling to the element<br>for example, I have three buttons and want to select the button just after <strong>save</strong> button</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;div class=\"post\">\n  &lt;button>save&lt;/button>\n  &lt;button>updated&lt;/button>\n  &lt;button>delete&lt;/button>\n&lt;/div>\n\n&lt;style>\n  .post button:first-child+button{color:red}\n&lt;/style></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"postarr\">\n  <button>save</button>\n  <button>updated</button>\n  <button>delete</button>\n</div>\n\n<style>\n  .postarr button:first-child+button{color:red}\n</style>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Pseudo Selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Pseudo selector is the next most powerful selector which solved many <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS\">css </a>problems to select the difficult selectable element. Types of pseudo selectors</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>:not()</strong><br>not is used to ignore the element between the selection of elements like children or other selectors<br>for example, I want to ignore 3<sub><sup>rd</sup></sub> child on a list then<br><code>ul li:not(:nth-of-type(3)){color:red}</code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>:focus-within</strong> - this selector gives us the power to select the parent of a focusable element<br>we can select the parent element and can style it. for example<code>,</code> I want to change the background of the form when focused on the email input<br><code>input[type=\"email\"]:focus-within{background:green}</code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>:empty()</strong><br>we can use an empty() pseudo selector for selecting an empty element ( the element which has no child or text).<br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>: <strong>after</strong> and : <strong>before</strong><br>These are the two selectors which are most useful in creating short pseudo-elements of design like corners, caret, borders, overlays,s, etc<br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":75,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://cms.frontendzone.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/css-selectors.jpg\" alt=\"css advanced slectors\" class=\"wp-image-75\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'CSS advanced selectors', 'Advanced css selector , rarely known by most of the developers . complete list of all advanced css selectors', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '72-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-07 19:23:36', '2023-02-07 19:23:36', '', 72, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=76', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(78, 1, '2023-02-07 19:56:35', '2023-02-07 19:56:35', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Problem statement: I have a sticky header and when I am clicking the table on the content link it\'s scrolled to the top and hidden behind the sticky header.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Solution</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>use the scroll-margin-top CSS property on the section to scroll to the top with the given margin</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>scroll-margin-top: 20px;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The table of content contains headings that need to be set on the scroll-margin-top equal to the height of the header</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.blog h1,\r\n.blog h2,\r\n.blog h3,\r\n.blog h4,\r\n.blog h5 {\r\n  scroll-margin-top: 80px;\r\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'How to fix hash navigation with a sticky header', 'How to fix hash navigation with a sticky header. solved table of content hash navigation section hidden behind header', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '38-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-07 19:56:35', '2023-02-07 19:56:35', '', 38, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=78', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(79, 1, '2023-02-07 20:02:36', '2023-02-07 20:02:36', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To update an object key in the state select the key and assign its value to that state</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>for example,</strong> if we have an object of books and we want to update the physics book name then we can do it in the following way</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":70,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://cms.frontendzone.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/usetsate-with-object-array.png\" alt=\"react hooks usestsate with object and array\" class=\"wp-image-70\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">react hooks usestsate with object and array</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Preserve previous value</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>use the spread operator(...) to preserve the previous value and only update the particular key so that no other keys override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Update the object key</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>{...prev, key</strong>: <strong>value</strong>} in object literal preserve the object\'s previous value and update the desired key </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>import { useState } from \"react\";\n\nconst demo = () =&gt; {\n  const &#91;books, setBooks] = useState({\n    physics: \"\",\n    chemistry: \"\",\n    math: \"\",\n  });\n  return (\n    &lt;div&gt;\n      &lt;p&gt;List of books&lt;/p&gt;\n      &lt;form&gt;\n        &lt;input\n          type=\"subject\"\n          name=\"book\"\n          onClick={(e) =&gt;\n            setBooks((prev) =&gt; ({\n              ...prev,\n              physics: e.target.value,\n            }))\n          }\n        /&gt;\n        &lt;button&gt;Update book&lt;/button&gt;\n      &lt;/form&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n  );\n};\n\nexport default demo;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>how to update array object key in useState</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the same, we can also update the array but in the array, we will have to map to preserve other items of the array and use a filter to update that particular item of the array.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>import { useState } from \"react\";\n\nconst demo = () =&gt; {\n  const &#91;faq, setFaq] = useState(&#91;\n    {\n      que: \"\",\n      ans: \"\",\n    },\n  ]);\n  return (\n    &lt;div&gt;\n      &lt;p&gt;List of books&lt;/p&gt;\n      &lt;form&gt;\n        &lt;input\n          type=\"subject\"\n          name=\"que\"\n          onClick={(e) =&gt;\n            setFaq((prev) =&gt;\n              prev.map((el, index) =&gt; {\n                if (index == i) {\n                  return {\n                    ...el,\n                    que: e.target.value,\n                  };\n                }\n              })\n            )\n          }\n        /&gt;\n        &lt;textarea\n          name=\"ans\"\n          onClick={(e) =&gt;\n            setFaq((prev) =&gt;\n              prev.map((el, index) =&gt; {\n                if (index == i) {\n                  return {\n                    ...el,\n                    ans: e.target.value,\n                  };\n                }\n              })\n            )\n          }\n        /&gt;\n        &lt;button&gt;Update book&lt;/button&gt;\n      &lt;/form&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n  );\n};\n\nexport default demo;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'how to set object key in useState, react state hook with the object and array', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '68-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-07 20:02:36', '2023-02-07 20:02:36', '', 68, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=79', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
