e nested object in usetstate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>  const &#91;data, setdata] = useState({\n    width: \"160\",\n    text: \"button\",\n    padding: \"17\",\n    border: {\n      width: \"1\",\n      type: \"solid\",\n      color: \"red\",\n      radius: \"20\",\n    },\n\n    background: {\n      isSolid: true,\n      color: \"red\",\n      gradient: { bg1: \"red\", bg2: \"blue\", angle: \"120\" },\n    },\n    textShadow: {\n      x: \"1\",\n      y: \"-1\",\n      blur: \"1\",\n      color: \"\",\n    },\n  });\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>above useState object is nested in 3 levels.<br>here I am updating the blur key of textshadow object</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;input type=\"range\"\n   onChange={(e) =&gt;setdata((prev) =&gt; ({\n                        ...prev,\n                        textShadow: {\n                          ...prev.textShadow,\n                          blur: e.target.value,\n                        },\n                      }))\n                    }\n/&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'how to set object key in useState, react state hook with the object and array', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '68-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-10 19:23:03', '2023-02-10 19:23:03', '', 68, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=95', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(98, 1, '2023-02-11 09:53:29', '2023-02-11 09:53:29', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>the array is a very important topic in javascript. Almost everywhere it is needed whether we are in frontend or backend with node js, so it becomes necessary to know javascript methods.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>declare an array in js </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>we can declare an array in js by following the methods</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const arr=&#91;\"1\",\"2\",\"3\"]\n         or\nconst arr=new Array(\"1\",\"2\",\"3\")</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>js length of an array</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const array=&#91;]\nconst length=array.length</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Push item to array in js</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const array=&#91;\"apple\",\"grapes\"]\narray.push(\"mango\")</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Find the item in the array</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>find()</code> the method returns the value of the first element that passes a test. We pass a filter function to check items that we want to find based on condition.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>find method run for every item in an array</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>it returns undefined if no item is found</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It does execute for an empty item</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>the find method does not change or manipulate the original array.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const array=&#91;\"mango\",\"apple\",\"grapes\"]\nconst findmango=array.find(el=>el==\"mango\")</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>filter array in js</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>filter method in an array is used to filter items from the array. we pass a function to filter items based on the condition it filters out the items in a new array.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The filter method does not execute the function on an empty element of the array</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The filter method does not change the original array.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The filter method creates a new array of items returned from the filter function.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const ages = &#91;32, 33, 16, 40];\nconst voters=ages.filter(el=>el>18)</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Js array findall</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>to find all items passed the particular conditions we will have to use the filter method</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const arr=&#91;10,20,22,50,60]\nconst all_items_above_21 = arr.filter(num=>num>21)</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>findindex method in js array</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The findindex method is used to find an index of an item in the array.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>find method executes a function for each element</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>JS empty an array</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There may be multiple ways to empty an array the easiest way is to assign an empty array.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const arr=&#91;\"12\",\"22\",\"17\"]</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Four ways to empty an array in javascript</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Pass empty array</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Set array length to zero</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Delete all elements using splice one by one</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Pop all items of an array.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>let a = &#91;1,2,3];\n\r\n//method 1\na = &#91;];\r\n\n//method 2\na.length = 0;\r\n\n//method 3\na.splice(0,a.length);\n\n//method 4\nwhile(a.length > 0) {\r\n    a.pop();\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>How to merge two arrays in js</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>to merge two arrays we can append two arrays using the append method or spread operator.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const arr1 = &#91;\"Cecilie\", \"Lone\"];\r\nconst arr2 = &#91;1, 2, 3];\n\n\r//method 1\nconst mergedArray = arr1.concat(arr2);\n\n//method 2\nconst mergedArray = &#91;...arr1,...arr2]\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Array concat method</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>concat method joins items of two or more arrays and returns a new array containing the items of all arrays. The Concat method does not change the original array.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>const arr1 = &#91;\"mango\", \"apple\"];\r\nconst arr2 = &#91;\"Emil\", \"Tobias\", \"Linus\"];\r\nconst arr3 = &#91;\"ashish\",\"manish\"];