n  See the Pen <a href=\"https://codepen.io/baahubali92/pen/qGWYXO\">\n  Simple Footer</a> by Baahubali (<a href=\"https://codepen.io/baahubali92\">@baahubali92</a>)\n  on <a href=\"https://codepen.io\">CodePen</a>.\n</iframe>\n<!-- /wp:html -->', 'HTML code example', 'HTML code example for login page , registration page , form and many more with html and css', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '107-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-16 18:13:54', '2023-02-16 18:13:54', '', 107, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=113', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(115, 1, '2023-02-16 18:15:55', '2023-02-16 18:15:55', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this article, we will know how to make a responsive sidebar  or navbar with <a href=\"/blog/html-code-example/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"/blog/html-code-example/\">HTML</a> and CSS for this you will need three things</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>use case</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Header</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>nav</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>ul</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>hamburger button for mobile</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>add active class to toggle sidebar to open &amp; close</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>source code</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\n\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;meta http-equiv=\"X-UA-Compatible\" content=\"IE=edge\"&gt;\n    &lt;meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;Document&lt;/title&gt;\n    &lt;style&gt;\n        * {\n            margin: 0;\n            padding: 0;\n        }\n\n        body {\n            font-family: sans-serif;\n        }\n\n        header {\n            padding: 1rem;\n            background: #000;\n            display: flex;\n            color: #fff;\n            justify-content: space-between;\n            align-items: center;\n            position: sticky;\n            top: 0;\n        }\n\n        header .brand {\n            text-decoration: none;\n            font-size: 20px;\n        }\n\n        header button {\n            width: 40px;\n            outline: none;\n            border: none;\n            padding: 10px;\n            background: transparent;\n            color: #fff;\n            display: none;\n            cursor: pointer;\n        }\n\n        header button span {\n            display: block;\n            height: 2px;\n            margin-bottom: 3px;\n            background: #fff;\n            width: 100%;\n        }\n\n        header a {\n            color: #fff;\n        }\n\n        nav ul li {\n            padding: 5px 10px;\n        }\n\n        nav ul {\n            display: flex;\n            list-style: none;\n        }\n\n\n        @media (max-width:767px) {\n            header button {\n                display: inline-block;\n            }\n\n            header nav {\n                position: absolute;\n                top: 100%;\n                left: -100%;\n                background: #000;\n                width: 70%;\n                transition: all 0.3s;\n                opacity: 0;\n            }\n\n            header::after {\n                content: \"\";\n                width: 100%;\n                position: absolute;\n                top: 100%;\n                left: 0;\n                height: 100vh;\n                z-index: -1;\n                background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7);\n                opacity: 0;\n                transition: all 0.3s;\n            }\n\n\n\n\n            header.active nav {\n                left: 0;\n                opacity: 1;\n            }\n\n            header.active::after {\n                opacity: 1;\n            }\n\n            header nav ul {\n                flex-direction: column;\n                height: 100vh;\n            }\n\n            nav ul li {\n                padding: 14px 10px;\n                border-bottom: 1px solid #f1f1f157;\n                display: block;\n            }\n        }\n    &lt;/style&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n\n&lt;body&gt;\n    &lt;header&gt;\n        &lt;a class=\"brand\" href=\"\"&gt;Website&lt;/a&gt;\n        &lt;button role=\"button\"&gt;\n            &lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;\n            &lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;\n            &lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;\n        &lt;/button&gt;\n        &lt;nav&gt;\n            &lt;ul&gt;\n                &lt;li&gt;Home&lt;/li&gt;\n                &lt;li&gt;Home&lt;/li&gt;\n                &lt;li&gt;Home&lt;/li&gt;\n                &lt;li&gt;Home&lt;/li&gt;\n                &lt;li&gt;Home&lt;/li&gt;\n            &lt;/ul&gt;\n        &lt;/nav&gt;\n    &lt;/header&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        document.querySelector(\"header button\").onclick = () =&gt; {\n            document.querySelector(\"header\").classList.toggle(\"active\")\n        }\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n\n&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Video</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<iframe width=\"100%\" height=\"415\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/8qsAdxa7hIE?start=10\" title=\"How to make a responsive sidebar/navbar with HTML and CSS\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe>\n<!-- /wp:html -->', 'How to make a responsive sidebar/navbar with HTML and CSS [demo & source code]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '54-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-16 18:15:55', '2023-02-16 18:15:55', '', 54, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=115', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(116, 1, '2023-02-17 11:54:11', '2023-02-17 11:54:11', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>CSS selectors</strong> are used to select HTML elements or groups of elements and apply CSS  on the selected nodes or elements. Mostly there are three types of <strong>selectors in CSS</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Class selector</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Id selector</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>tag name selector</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The above are just basic selectors but when you have complex designs then you will need some advanced types of selectors, let\'s know what are other <strong>advanced CSS selectors</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Child selector (div p)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>general sibling selector (.main ~ button )</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>attributes  selector ( [class*=\"active\"] )</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Pseudo selectors (:hover,:active,:last-child,:first-child, :not,:where)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Descendent selector (div&gt;p)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adjacent sibling selector (sibling1 + sibling 2)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Universal selector (*)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now let\'s know them one by one in detail</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Child selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A child selector is used to select children elements of an element. for example, if you want to select all p tags inside a div with the class name \"post\" then children will be selected with </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.post p</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>General sibling selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the most powerful selector. Most of the time when you have no solution to select a tag there always remains a possibility that we can select that with the general sibling selector. The general sibling selector selects <strong>all sibling elements of that element</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\n\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;meta http-equiv=\"X-UA-Compatible\" content=\"IE=edge\"&gt;\n    &lt;meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;Document&lt;/title&gt;\n    &lt;style&gt;\n        .post&gt;.readmore~button {\n            background: red;\n            padding:10px;\n            border:none;\n            outline:none\n        }\n    &lt;/style&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n\n&lt;body&gt;\n    &lt;div class=\"main\"&gt;\n        &lt;div class=\"post\"&gt;\n            &lt;button class=\"readmore\"&gt;read more&lt;/button&gt;\n            &lt;button&gt;read more1&lt;/button&gt;\n            &lt;button&gt;read more2&lt;/button&gt;\n            &lt;button&gt;read more3&lt;/button&gt;\n        &lt;/div&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;/body&gt;\n\n&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<style>\n        .postart>.readmore ~ button {\n            background: red;\n            padding:10px;\n            border:none;\n            outline:none\n        }\n    </style>\n\n    <div class=\"main\">\n        <div class=\"postart\">\n            <button class=\"readmore\">read more</button>\n            <button>read more1</button>\n            <button>read more2</button>\n            <button>read more3</button>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Attribute selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>HTML element can also be selected based on its attribute whether it\'s a default or custom attribute.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>syntax of attribute selector</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;attribute=\"attribute-value\"]{\n\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>example </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&#91;class*=\"col\"]{\npadding:-15px\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>some of the advanced methods of attribute selectors</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class*=\"col\"]<br>attribute value has a \"col\" word somewhere example : <code><code>&lt;div class=\"<strong>col</strong>-md-4\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code></code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class^=\"col-12\"]<br>attribute value has a \"<strong>col</strong>\" word in starting example : <code>&lt;div class=\"<strong>col-12</strong> col-md-4\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class$=\"col\"]<br>class tribute has the value \"<strong>col-12</strong>\" word at the end <br>example : <code>&lt;div class=\"<code>col-md-4</code> <strong>col-12</strong>\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>[class=\"col\"] <br>the attribute value is exactly \"col\"<br>example <code>&lt;div class=\"<code>col</code>\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Adjacent sibling selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An adjacent sibling selector is used to select just the next sibling to the element<br>for example, I have three buttons and want to select the button just after <strong>save</strong> button</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;div class=\"post\"&gt;\n  &lt;button&gt;save&lt;/button&gt;\n  &lt;button&gt;updated&lt;/button&gt;\n  &lt;button&gt;delete&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;style&gt;\n  .post button:first-child+button{color:red}\n&lt;/style&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"postarr\">\n  <button>save</button>\n  <button>updated</button>\n  <button>delete</button>\n</div>\n\n<style>\n  .postarr button:first-child+button{color:red}\n</style>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Pseudo Selector</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Pseudo selector is the next most powerful selector which solved many <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS\">css </a>problems to select the difficult selectable element. Types of pseudo selectors</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>:not()</strong><br>not is used to ignore the element between the selection of elements like children or other selectors<br>for example, I want to ignore 3<sub><sup>rd</sup></sub> child on a list then<br><code>ul li:not(:nth-of-type(3)){color:red}</code><br><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>:focus-within</strong> - this selector gives us the power to select the parent of a focusable element<br>we can select the parent element and can style it. for example<code>,</code> I want to change the background of the form when focused on the email input<br><code>input[type=\"email\"]:focus-within{background:green}</code><br><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>:empty()</strong><br>we can use an empty() pseudo selector for selecting an empty element ( the element which has no child or text).<br><br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>: <strong>after</strong> and : <strong>before</strong><br>These are the two selectors which are most useful in creating short pseudo-elements of design like corners, caret, borders, overlays,s, etc<br></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":75,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://cms.frontendzone.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/css-selectors.jpg\" alt=\"css advanced slectors\" class=\"wp-image-75\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'CSS advanced selectors', 'Advanced css selector ,[class=\"red\"] rarely known by most of the developers . complete list of all advanced css selectors', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '72-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-17 11:54:11', '2023-02-17 11:54:11', '', 72, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=116', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
