ng> properties.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>div{\n  position: static;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>position : fixed</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The fixed position is used to fix an element in HTML. If you want to fix an element in HTML structure you can use fixed position. Position fixed works relative to the viewport, the element with position fixed always stays at its position even if the page is scrolled. For <strong>example </strong>- The WhatsApp button is fixed on the right bottom of the websites. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>top, left, right,</strong> and <strong>bottom</strong> properties are used to position an element with a position fixed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>div{\nposition:fixed;\ntop:0;\nleft:0;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Static</td><td>default position<br><em><strong>position: static;</strong></em></td></tr><tr><td>absolute</td><td>To position an element in an element on the specific position<br><em><strong>position: absolute</strong></em></td></tr><tr><td>relative</td><td>To position an element relative to itself<br><strong><em>position: relative</em></strong></td></tr><tr><td>fixed</td><td>To fix the element relative to the viewport<br><strong><em>position: fixed</em></strong></td></tr><tr><td>sticky</td><td>position toggled between <strong>fixed</strong> and <strong>relative</strong><br><strong><em>position: sticky</em></strong></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>position : absolute</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Position absolute is used to position an element relative to an element in CSS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example: </strong>You want to fix a button in a div at a specific position.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;div class=\"post\">\n    &lt;p>how to fix div in css&lt;/p>\n   &lt;button>read more&lt;/button>\n&lt;div></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.post{postion:relative}\n.post button{\n  position:absolute;\n  left:0;\n  bottom:0\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":125,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image aligncenter size-full\"><img src=\"https://cms.frontendzone.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/div-css-postion.jpg\" alt=\"how to change the position of div in CSS \" class=\"wp-image-125\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>position : sticky</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><code>position:sticky</code>  is used to stick the element in a specified position from an element when scrolling. For example - a sticky header on a webpage</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A sticky element\'s position is toggled between <code>fixed</code> and <code>relative</code>. The element is positioned as relative until the specified offset is met in the viewport or parent element. If offset is met the element is positioned as <code>fixed</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>header{\nposition:sticky;\ntop:0;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>If you are using position absolute make sure its parent position is nonstatic (other than position: static) otherwise your desired result can\'t be made.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'how to change the position of div in CSS ', 'To change the position of a div there are multiple ways. You can change the position of the div by changing the top, left, right, and bottom properties of a div position if it is set to position fixed or absolute', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '124-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-18 16:58:58', '2023-02-18 16:58:58', '', 124, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=135', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
