(170, 1, '2023-02-24 20:20:57', '2023-02-24 20:20:57', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The error message you\'re seeing indicates that your code is trying to import a module called <code>react-dom/client</code> from a file named <code>pure.js</code>, but it cannot find the module.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a few possible reasons for this error:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>The <code>react-dom</code> the package is not installed in your project. Make sure you have installed it using a package manager like npm or yarn.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>You have an outdated version of <code>react-dom</code>. The <code>client </code>module was removed in React 18, so if you\'re using an older version of <code>react-dom</code>, it may not have the <code>client</code> module. Try upgrading to the latest version of <code>react-dom</code>.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>The path to the <code>react-dom/client</code> the module is incorrect. Double-check the path in your import statement to make sure it is pointing to the correct location.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>There is a typo or other error in your code. Check for any syntax errors or other issues in your code that might be causing the import to fail.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have resolved the issue, the <code>react-dom/client</code> module should be imported successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to fix this error \"cannot find module \'react-dom/client\' from \'pure.js\'\"', 'cannot find module \'react-dom/client\' from \'pure.js\'', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cannot-find-module-react-dom-client-from-pure-js', '', '', '2023-03-25 11:46:57', '2023-03-25 11:46:57', '', 0, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=170', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(171, 1, '2023-02-24 20:20:57', '2023-02-24 20:20:57', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The error message you\'re seeing indicates that your code is trying to import a module called <code>react-dom/client</code> from a file named <code>pure.js</code>, but it cannot find the module.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a few possible reasons for this error:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>The <code>react-dom</code> the package is not installed in your project. Make sure you have installed it using a package manager like npm or yarn.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>You have an outdated version of <code>react-dom</code>. The <code>client </code>module was removed in React 18, so if you\'re using an older version of <code>react-dom</code>, it may not have the <code>client</code> module. Try upgrading to the latest version of <code>react-dom</code>.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>The path to the <code>react-dom/client</code> the module is incorrect. Double-check the path in your import statement to make sure it is pointing to the correct location.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><p>There is a typo or other error in your code. Check for any syntax errors or other issues in your code that might be causing the import to fail.</p></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have resolved the issue, the <code>react-dom/client</code> module should be imported successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'cannot find module \'react-dom/client\' from \'pure.js\'', 'cannot find module \'react-dom/client\' from \'pure.js\'', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '170-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-24 20:20:57', '2023-02-24 20:20:57', '', 170, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=171', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(172, 1, '2023-02-24 20:27:20', '2023-02-24 20:27:20', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is possible to use React with ASP.NET Web Forms, but it requires some additional setup and configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One approach is to create a new ASP.NET Web Forms application and then add React to it as a client-side library. You can use a package manager like npm or yarn to install React and its dependencies, and then include the React scripts in your Web Forms pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the basic steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create a new ASP.NET Web Forms application in Visual Studio.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Install Node.js and npm (Node.js package manager) on your system.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open a command prompt or terminal and navigate to the root directory of your project.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use the package manager (npm or yarn) to install React and its dependencies. For example, you can run the following command to install React:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create a new ASP.NET Web Forms application in Visual Studio.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Install Node.js and npm (Node.js package manager) on your system.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open a command prompt or terminal and navigate to the root directory of your project.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use the package manager (npm or yarn) to install React and its dependencies. For example, you can run the following command to install React:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/react/16.8.6/umd/react.development.js\">&lt;/script>\r\n&lt;script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/react-dom/16.8.6/umd/react-dom.development.js\">&lt;/script>\r\n&lt;script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/babel-standalone/6.26.0/babel.min.js\">&lt;/script>\r\n&lt;script src=\"Scripts/app.jsx\" type=\"text/babel\">&lt;/script>\r\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that you should include these scripts at the bottom of your HTML pages, just before the closing <code>&lt;/body></code> tag, to ensure that the DOM has been fully loaded before your React code runs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That\'s it! With these steps, you can use React to build dynamic UIs in your ASP.NET Web Forms application. However, keep in mind that this approach requires some additional setup and configuration compared to using React with a more modern framework like React or Angular.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to use react js with asp.net web forms ', 'How to use react js with asp.net web forms ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-use-react-js-with-asp-net-web-forms', '', '', '2023-02-24 20:27:21', '2023-02-24 20:27:21', '', 0, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=172', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(173, 1, '2023-02-24 20:27:20', '2023-02-24 20:27:20', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is possible to use React with ASP.NET Web Forms, but it requires some additional setup and configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One approach is to create a new ASP.NET Web Forms application and then add React to it as a client-side library. You can use a package manager like npm or yarn to install React and its dependencies, and then include the React scripts in your Web Forms pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the basic steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create a new ASP.NET Web Forms application in Visual Studio.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Install Node.js and npm (Node.js package manager) on your system.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open a command prompt or terminal and navigate to the root directory of your project.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use the package manager (npm or yarn) to install React and its dependencies. For example, you can run the following command to install React:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create a new ASP.NET Web Forms application in Visual Studio.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Install Node.js and npm (Node.js package manager) on your system.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open a command prompt or terminal and navigate to the root directory of your project.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use the package manager (npm or yarn) to install React and its dependencies. For example, you can run the following command to install React:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/react/16.8.6/umd/react.development.js\">&lt;/script>\r\n&lt;script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/react-dom/16.8.6/umd/react-dom.development.js\">&lt;/script>\r\n&lt;script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/babel-standalone/6.26.0/babel.min.js\">&lt;/script>\r\n&lt;script src=\"Scripts/app.jsx\" type=\"text/babel\">&lt;/script>\r\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that you should include these scripts at the bottom of your HTML pages, just before the closing <code>&lt;/body></code> tag, to ensure that the DOM has been fully loaded before your React code runs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That\'s it! With these steps, you can use React to build dynamic UIs in your ASP.NET Web Forms application. However, keep in mind that this approach requires some additional setup and configuration compared to using React with a more modern framework like React or Angular.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to use react js with asp.net web forms ', 'How to use react js with asp.net web forms ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '172-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-02-24 20:27:20', '2023-02-24 20:27:20', '', 172, 'https://cms.frontendzone.com/?p=173', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
